'''Suitengu Hiranuma Shrine''' (水天宮平沼神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|12=draft|12=draft}}{{ill|Yokohama City|ja|横浜市|12=draft|12=draft}}{{ill|Nishi-ku|ja|西区|12=draft|lt=Nishi Ward|12=draft}} {{ill|Hiranuma|ja|平沼|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|村社|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is also known as the former guardian shrine of Hiranuma Shinden and serves as the ujigami for the area around the east exit of {{ill|Yokohama Station|ja|横浜駅|12=draft|12=draft}}.

==Enshrined Deities==
* {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天御中主神|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Antoku Tennō|ja|安徳天皇|1=Emperor Antoku|2=ja|3=安徳天皇|4=de|5=Antoku|12=draft|12=draft}}

Antoku Tennō is the deity of {{ill|Suitengu|ja|水天宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, and is revered as a god of easy childbirth and water. Not only did he remain intact during the {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|12=draft|12=draft}} 12 ({{ill|1923|ja|1923rd year|12=draft|12=draft}}) {{ill|Kantō Great Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|12=draft|12=draft}}, but he was also spared from conflagration during a nearby fire, and even amid the scorched-earth devastation of Yokohama during the Yokohama air raid on May 29, {{ill|1945|ja|1945th year|12=draft|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}} era, one corner of the shrine’s precincts remained unburned. For these reasons, he is venerated as a protector against fire disasters.

==History==
[[File:Hon-numaBashi1860.jpg|thumb|Once enshrined at the base of Hon-numa Bridge (present-day {{ill|Hiranuma Bridge|ja|平沼橋|12=draft|12=draft}} as Former Hiranuma Bridge) (from Utagawa Sadahide’s “List of Yokohama Landmarks”, circa 1860)]]
In the latter part of the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, in {{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|12=draft|12=draft}} 10 ({{ill|1839|ja|1839th year|12=draft|12=draft}}), Hiranuma Kyūbee (the 5th generation) is said to have first enshrined the deity.

According to the shrine legend, the Hiranuma area at that time was known for its {{ill|Salt Fields|ja|塩田|12=draft|12=draft}}, and villagers working in the salt fields discovered a small shrine {{ill|Small Shrine|ja|祠|12=draft|12=draft}} that had drifted into the cove. Every time they attempted to return it to the sea, it would float back to the shore. When they reported this phenomenon to Kyūbee, he interpreted it as a divine revelation to enshrine it in this land that lacked a {{ill|Guardian Deity|ja|守護神|12=draft|12=draft}}, and so he raised it to the shore and established it as the guardian deity of Hiranuma Shinden. Moreover, because a deity tablet from the {{ill|Suitengu (Kurume)|ja|水天宮 (久留米市)|lt=Suitengu|lt_ja=水天宮|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Chikugo Province|ja|筑後国|lt=Chikugo|lt_ja=筑後|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Kurume City|ja|久留米市|lt=Kurume|lt_ja=久留米|12=draft|12=draft}}) was enshrined within the small shrine, it came to be known as “Suitengu” and was widely revered as a god of easy childbirth and water.

Originally, the shrine was enshrined near the {{ill|Kazamaki River|ja|帷子川|12=draft|12=draft}} (now known as Imai River) that flows through what is now Nishihiranuma-cho in Nishi Ward, Yokohama, near the bridge {{ill|Hiranuma Bridge|ja|平沼橋|lt=Former Hiranuma Bridge|lt_ja=元平沼橋|12=draft|12=draft}}. With subsequent development, the location of the shrine was relocated several times, with the current relocation taking place in {{ill|Bunkyū|ja|文久|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 ({{ill|1863|ja|1863rd year|12=draft|12=draft}}). Under the modern shrine ranking system of the {{ill|Meiji Government|ja|明治政府|12=draft|12=draft}}, it was officially renamed “Hiranuma Shrine” as the village shrine of Hiranuma, and in {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|12=draft|12=draft}} 2 ({{ill|1913|ja|1913rd year|12=draft|12=draft}}) a new worship hall ({{ill|Worship Hall|ja|拝殿|12=draft|12=draft}}) was constructed in front of the main hall ({{ill|Main Hall|ja|本殿|12=draft|12=draft}}), forming the current shrine complex.

Although the shrine was originally named “Suitengu,” and was later renamed “Hiranuma Shrine” under {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}} reforms, it continued to be venerated as Yokohama’s Suitengu. On both prewar and postwar city maps published by Yokohama, it is still labeled “Suitengu,” and even today parishioners and devotees refer to it as “Suitengu Hiranuma Shrine.”

==Subsidiary Shrines==
Within the precincts are Hiranuma Inari Shrine, Inari Shrine, Kamameshihara Shrine, and Hiranuma Tenmangu.

==Festivals and Annual Events==
* Annual Festival: September 5 (featuring {{ill|Food Stalls|ja|屋台|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Vendor Operations|ja|営業|12=draft|12=draft}}, and a mikoshi procession [{{ill|Divine Procession|ja|神幸祭|lt=Mikoshi Procession|lt_ja=神輿渡御|12=draft|12=draft}}] as well as events held in the {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|lt=Kagura Hall|lt_ja=神楽殿|12=draft|12=draft}})
* Yunohana Ritual (Yunotachi Ritual): January 5

==Parishioner Areas==
* Nishi Ward: {{ill|Hiranuma|ja|平沼|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Nishi Ward, Nishi-Hiranuma Town
* Nishi Ward: {{ill|Takashima|ja|高島|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Nishi Ward, Midorimachi
* Nishi Ward: {{ill|Minato Mirai 21|ja|横浜みなとみらい21|lt=Minato Mirai|lt_ja=みなとみらい|12=draft|12=draft}} (partly; formerly Midorimachi)

==Location and Access==
Kanagawa Prefecture, Yokohama City, Nishi Ward, Hiranuma 2-8-20
* {{ill|Hiranuma Bridge Station|ja|平沼橋駅|12=draft|12=draft}} (Sotetsu) – 1 minute on foot
* {{ill|Tobe Station|ja|戸部駅|12=draft|12=draft}} (Keikyu) – 5 minutes on foot

==Notes==
* The shrine mon is a “chain-attached anchor.”
* The issuance of goshuin (shrine stamps) has not been available since {{ill|2013|ja|2013rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heisei 25).

==Related Articles==
* {{ill|Suitengu|ja|水天宮|12=draft|12=draft}}

==External Links==
* [http://www.hiranuma-suitengu.or.jp/index.html {{ill|Suitengu Hiranuma Shrine Website|ja|水天宮平沼神社サイト|12=draft|12=draft}}]

